comment_data.body:
Also have this issue, in NixOS. 
- in Alt-F1 etc. consoles, with TERM=linux, Ctrl-Z doesn't work. (It works correctly with the same neovim in xterm in Alt-F7 graphical console, where TERM=xterm.)
- when I run `:suspend` or `:stop`, they execute successfully and throw me to shell, where `fg` restores nvim;
- in insert mode, nothing seems to happen on Ctrl-Z either; even if I do Ctrl-V, pressing Ctrl-Z still does nothing (a `^` is still displayed, waiting for some keypress);
- I tried adding a signal handler for SIGTSTP in src/nvim/os/signal.c, printing some text to a file, but it was not called (the file was not created) on Ctrl-Z; the same code inserted on first line of signal_init resulted in the file being created, so it was not a bug in the debugging code;
- I tried `kill -TSTP $PID` from another console; it stopped neovim, but in a weird way: the `[1]+ Stopped   bin/nvim` message got printed at the top of the screen, and vim's screen stayed visible "in background" (instead of vim's screen scrolling up and the "Stopped" message showing below it). Then after `fg`, vim doesn't register keys immediately, only after <CR> (even Ctrl-L gets handled only after a subsequent <CR>).

It looks to me like the keypress doesn't get converted into SIGTSTP somehow? weird. No idea what can do it, such that even a registered SIGTSTP handler doesn't get called! Also, for other programs (e.g. less), Ctrl-Z works fine.
